Java interop — every jar is yours.

Because Scala compiles to java virtual machine bytecode that looks indistinguishable from java's, any java library is automatically a Scala library. There is no foreign function interface, no binding layer, no wrappers needed.

In practice this means the entire java standard library is in scope — java time local date, java util u-u-i-d, java n-i-o file path — all callable from Scala with the same method signatures. Every artifact on maven central, the java virtual machine's package registry, is one line in your build file away from being a dependency. A Scala class can extend a java class, and a java class can extend a Scala class — same extends keyword, same single-inheritance rules.

There are three friction points, in order of how often you will trip over them.

The first is null. Java application programming interfaces return null to signal absence; Scala uses option instead. Wrap a java return in option at the boundary to stop nulls from leaking into your Scala code. Notebook six covers this.

The second is checked exceptions. Java has them; Scala does not. You catch them in Scala using the same try and catch, but the compiler will not force you to.

The third is collection conversions. A java util list is not a scala list. Import the scala j-d-k collection converters and call as-scala or as-java to convert at the seam.

You will see all three of these in the Spark code you read later. Spark's java application programming interface layer is the canonical example of working across this boundary.
